    <text>
        <body>
            <div>
                <head>Translated parts</head>
                <p xml:id="KR6r0138-start">
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b1501.s18" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">Imperial decree reply.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b1501.s19" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">Once one attains non-form, all existences are completely forgotten.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b1501.s20" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">Further inquiry.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b1501.s21" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">Yī dé wú xiàng, wàng wàn yǒu zhě.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b1501.s22" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">may also attain an empty mind to exhaustively explore that true realm;</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b1501.s23" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">one should not gradually perceive it.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b1501.s24" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">Imperial decree reply.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b1501.s25" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">The Tathāgata's comprehension of stillness is naturally an exhaustive exploration of truth.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b1501.s26" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">Saints of shallow practice invariably perceive it gradually.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b1501.s27" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">Further inquiry.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b1501.s28" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">If one sees truth as something to be gradually perceived, one cannot suddenly comprehend it.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b1501.s29" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">One should also gradually forget all existences, which cannot be suddenly forgotten.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b1501.s30" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">Imperial decree reply.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b1501.s31" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">Because understandings have superior and inferior levels, there is gradual perception.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b1501.s32" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">Because forgetting the mind has no bias, all existences are simultaneously stilled.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b26.s1" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">Imperial decree explaining the meaning of Dharmakāya.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b2701.s1" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">Dharmakāya is empty and still.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b2701.s2" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">It is far from the realm of being and non-being.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b2701.s3" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">It is uniquely liberated beyond cause and effect.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b2701.s4" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">It cannot be known by wisdom.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b2701.s5" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">It cannot be recognized by consciousness.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b2701.s6" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">How can it be argued about by appellations?</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b2701.s7" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">Intending to reveal the principle, silence is not permissible.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b2701.s8" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">Therefore, we follow speech.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b2701.s9" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">Thus, there is the appellation Dharmakāya.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b2701.s10" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">In India, it is called Dharmaśarīra.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b2701.s11" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">In this land (China), it is called Dharmakāya.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b2701.s12" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">If according to its very essence, it is the designation of self-nature.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b2701.s13" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">If according to speech, then it is a relatively established name.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b2701.s14" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">"Dharma" signifies norm or principle.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b2701.s15" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">"Kāya" has the meaning of possessing substance.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b2701.s16" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">The substance of norm is why it is called Dharmakāya.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b2701.s17" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">Briefly adhering to speech, we roughly present its substance.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6r0138_CBETA_021-0250b2701.s18" xml:lang="en" resp="#gemini-2.0-flash" modified="2025-05-16T09:52:16.508+09:00">It is the permanent body.</seg>
                </p>
            </div>
